A Federal High Court in Lagos has restrained the National Insurance Commission (NAICOM) from implementing its proposed minimum solvency capital policy scheduled to take effect from October 1, 2018, pending the expiration of a 30-day pre-action notice. Justice Muslim Hassan,  gave the order in a class action brought by some shareholders of insurance companies in Nigeria, challenging the new minimum solvency capital policy proposed by the NAICOM. At the hearing, counsel to the applicant, Bert Chucks Igwilo, told the court that they had filed and served the NAICOM a pre-action notice on Sept 6. Justice Hassan gave the order and adjourned further hearing to Oct 8. 